\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 1.  Application Installation (AppInstall) Overview
\par ------------------------------------------------------------------
\par 
\par 1.1.\tab What is AppInstall?
\par 
\par Application Installation (AppInstall) is the mechanism used to install Windows CE applications to a Windows CE device.  AppInstall supports multiple installation methods, such as desktop-to-de
vice, web-to-device, Storage Card-to-device, and device-to-device.
\par 
\par It is comprised of 3 tools - CAB Wizard (CabWiz), Application Manager (AppMgr), and WCELoad.  CAB Wizard is the desktop SDK tool that packages your application binaries into a single Windows CE CAB file.  Application Manager is the desktop ActiveSync
 component that provides the user a desktop-to-device application management tool.  WCELoad is the Windows CE tool that unpacks a Windows CE CAB file to install your application to the device.
\par 
\par 
\par 1.2.\tab Where can I get it?
\par 
\par CAB Wizard is used by the application creator, and is part of the Windows CE SDK.  Application Manager is used by both the application creator and the end-user, and is included with every installation of ActiveSync
.  WCELoad is used by the end-user, and is included with most Windows CE devices.
\par 
\par 
\par 1.3.\tab Where is the documentation?
\par 
\par The Application Installation documentation is part of the Windows CE SDK Programmer's Guide, under the Connection Services section.  This documentation includes the input file to CabW
iz (the CabWiz INF file), the input file to AppMgr (the AppMgr INI file), as well as samples of both files.
\par 
\par Also, the input to CAB Wizard (the CabWiz INF file) uses a modified Win32 INF file format.  The Win32 INF file format is documented in the Win32 Platform SDK documentation, under the Setup API section.
\par 
\par 
\par 1.4.\tab What other resources are there?
\par 
\par http://www.microsoft.com/windowsce provides information about Windows CE, and any future news.
\par http://www.microsoft.com/events/windowsce provides information about the Windows CE Developer Conference, and currently includes a slide presentation about AppInstall.
\par http://support.microsoft.com provides Knowledge Base (KB) articles on known issues.
\par 
\par Also, the latest version of the Windows CE SDK (which includes support for the Palm-size PC devices) contains a complete Blackjack Sample application that can be used as a template.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.  CAB Wizard (CabWiz)
\par ----------------------------------
\par 
\par 2.1.\tab What does CabWiz do?
\par 
\par CabWiz is the desktop SDK tool that packages your application binaries into a single Windows CE CAB file.  It uses a CabWiz INF file, which contains setup commands such as where to copy device files, and what device registry settings to make.  With the Ca
bWiz INF file and your application binaries, it will create multiple platform-specific Windows CE CAB files, which is used to install your application to a Windows CE device.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.2.\tab What is a CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par A CabWiz INF file is a modified version of the 
Win32 INF file format.  The Win32 INF file format is a documented Win32 format used to describe setup commands, such as copying files and creating registry settings.  The CabWiz INF file format uses the Win32 INF file format, with various INF commands add
ed and removed.  A single CabWiz INF file is used by CabWiz to create a CAB file for each targeted platform (such as the H/PC or Palm-size PC).
\par 
\par 
\par 2.3.\tab What is a Windows CE CAB file?
\par 
\par A Windows CE CAB file is a Win32 CAB file containing Windows CE-specific f
iles.  The Win32 CAB file is the Microsoft file format used for compressing and distributing multiple files.  The Windows CE CAB file uses the Win32 CAB file format to store the setup information (the CabWiz INF file) plus your device-side application bin
a
ries.  A single CAB file contains device-specific binaries for a targeted platform (such as the H/PC on a MIPS CPU, or a Palm-size PC on an SH3 CPU).  This means that CabWiz can be used to create a number of CAB files, each CAB file for a specific device 
type.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.4.\tab How do I call CabWiz?
\par 
\par Running CabWiz without any parameters will provide a usage message box.  The important thing to note is to call CabWiz with a double-quoted absolute path to the CabWiz INF file.  Also, to have CabWiz create multiple CAB f
iles for supporting multiple device types, you will need to use the "/cpu" flag followed by a set of Platform Labels (described in a later section).
\par 
\par 
\par 2.5.\tab Can CabWiz INF files be used for installing on Win9x or WinNT?
\par 
\par No.  CabWiz INF files are only speci
fic to Windows CE, and cannot be used for installing on Win9x or WinNT machines.  Also, Win32 INF files (created for Win9x or WinNT) cannot be used on Windows CE.  However, you can use a Win32 INF file as a template - a CabWiz INF file is a Win32 INF file
 with various INF commands added and removed.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.6.\tab What other support files are used by CabWiz?
\par 
\par CabWiz is installed with 2 other support files: MakeCab.exe and CabWiz.ddf.  Both these files must be in the same directory as CabWiz.exe.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.7.\tab Can I create a Windows CE CAB file using "makecab.exe"?
\par 
\par No.  MakeCab.exe is the actual program that will create CAB files - however, it will not incorporate the setup information provided in your CabWiz INF file.  CabWiz.exe is the program to use to create Windows CE CAB files.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.8.\tab What are Directory IDs, and how do I use them?
\par 
\par CabWiz INF Directory IDs are identifiers used to specify standard device directories in the CabWiz INF file, such as "\\Windows" and "\\Windows\\Start Menu".  The format of a Direc
tory ID is %CEx%, where "x" is a number.  These Directory IDs will be replaced with the full path at device application installation runtime.  The list of all supported CabWiz INF Directory IDs for H/PCs and Palm-size PCs are documented in the Windows CE 
SDK.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.9.\tab What are Platform Labels, and how do I use them?
\par 
\par Platform Labels are used to make CabWiz create multiple platform-specific CAB files from a single CabWiz INF file.  The Platform Labels tells CabWiz how many CAB files to generate, where to get t
he CPU-specific binary files, and the platform information to incorporate into the CAB file, so that for example, the end-user will not be able to install an H/PC SH3 processor CAB file on to a Palm-size PC MIPS processor device.
\par 
\par Platform Labels are uniqu
e labels that are appended to specific sections in the CabWiz INF file (see the Windows CE SDK docs).  The main section that differentiates the platforms is the [CEDevice] INF section, which allows for device-specific information, such as the processor ty
pe, the device types (H/PC or Palm-size PC) supported, the Windows CE OS version supported, etc.  These Platform Labels also need to be specified in the command-line parameters when invoking CabWiz.
\par 
\par A full example of using Platform Labels is found in the Blackjack Sample application included with the latest version of the Windows CE SDK (which includes support for the Palm-size PC devices).
\par 
\par 
\par 2.10.\tab How do I use a literal % (percent) symbol in the CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par Use %% in the CabWiz INF file to represent a single literal % symbol.  However, this cannot be used under the [Strings] section, since every string under the [Strings] section needs to be enclosed by % symbols to perform string substitutions.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.11.\tab How do I use a literal double-quote (") symbol in the CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par Use "" in the CabWiz INF file to represent a literal double-quote (").
\par 
\par 
\par 2.12.\tab Things to check for when encountering errors with CabWiz
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 - The Windows CE SDK-included files "MakeCab.exe" and "CabWiz.ddf" must be in the same directory as "CabWiz.exe"
\par - Call "CabWiz.exe" with double-quoted absolute path
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 - Use a double-quoted absolute path for the CabWiz INF file parameter
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 - Verify in the INF file that string lists do not have trailing commas or unnecessary/extra spaces - example:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 \tab Invalid:\tab CopyFiles=Files.Common,  Files.Cpu,
\par \tab Valid:\tab CopyFiles=Files.Common,Files.Cpu
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 
\par 
\par 3.  Application Manager (AppMgr)
\par -----------------------------------------------
\par 
\par 3.1.\tab What does AppMgr do?
\par 
\par AppMgr is the desktop tool installed by ActiveSync that provides desktop-to-device application management, similar to Windows Add/Remove Programs.  To provide information about your device app to AppMgr, you 
will need to invoke AppMgr with an AppMgr INI file, which contains app information such as where the CAB files are located.  With the AppMgr INI file and the location of the CAB files, AppMgr can be used by the end-user to install and remove the app to an
d from the device.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.2.\tab What is an AppMgr INI file?
\par 
\par An AppMgr INI file is a text file containing information about your application, such as description text, display icon, and uninstall information.  A required piece of information is a list of Windows 
CE CAB files that contain your device app.  The AppMgr INI file is used as input into AppMgr, to provide it knowledge of your installed app.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.3.\tab How do I call AppMgr?
\par 
\par End-users can invoke AppMgr through ActiveSync
 (from the tools menu).  The application creator needs to invoke AppMgr with an AppMgr INI file, to provide information about the creator's device application.  The important thing to note is to call AppMgr with a double-quoted absolute path to the AppMgr
 INI file.  The full path of AppMgr can be found from the desktop registry - it is stored in the default registry value of "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\CurrentVersion\\App Paths\\CEAPPMGR.EXE".
\par 
\par 
\par 3.4.\tab Where can I find the location of AppMgr on the user's desktop machine?
\par 
\par The full path of AppMgr can be found from the desktop registry - it is stored in the default registry value of "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\CurrentVersion\\App Paths\\CEAPPMGR.EXE".
\par 
\par 
\par 3.5.\tab How do I create a single setup program to support both v1 and v2 devices?
\par 
\par v1 devices still requires the use of PPCLoad to install the application to the device, while v2 (and future) devices will use the Application Installation mechanism.  You can create a single setup program to support both v1 and v2 devices using
 the following pseudocode:
\par 
\par // early in setup, determine the installation method
\par if "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\App Paths\\CEAppMgr.EXE" registry key exists then
\par \tab use v2 AppInstall
\par else if "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Pegasus\\InstalledDir" registry value exists then
\par \tab use v1 PPCLoad
\par else
\par \tab neither HPC Explorer nor ActiveSync is installed - exit setup
\par endif
\par ...
\par // late in setup, copy the files and install to device
\par if using v2 AppInstall then
\par \tab copy .CAB and .INI files to desktop PC
\par \tab launch CEAppMgr with full file/path to the .INI file
\par else
\par \tab copy application's SH3 and MIPS binaries and .LOAD file to desktop PC
\par \tab ask user to connect their device
\par \tab get the connected-device processor type (from "HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Pegasus\\CPU" registry value)
\par \tab call PPCLoad::Load_Init()
\par \tab call PPCLoad::Load() with the CPU information, full file/path of the .LOAD file, etc.
\par \tab call PPCLoad::Exit()
\par endif
\par 
\par 
\par 3.6.\tab Where does AppMgr get the full application name from?
\par 
\par AppMgr will get your full application name from the CAB file itself.  It will concatenate the "Provider" and "AppName" values from the CabWiz INF file to create the full application name.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.7.\tab Things to check for when encountering errors with AppMgr
\par 
\par - Use a double-quoted absolute path for the AppMgr INI file(s) parameter
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 - Use the "/report" parameter in debug versions to verify that AppMgr is using the correct information for the CAB files.
\par - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string list in the "CabFiles" key contains no unnecessary spaces.  Example:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1800\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 \tab Invalid:\tab CabFiles=app.sh3.cab,  app.mips.cab
\par \tab Valid:\tab CabFiles=app.sh3.cab,app.mips.cab
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string list in the "CabFiles" key matches the actual CAB files name and relative path.
\par - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string value in the "Component" key exists elsewhere in the INI file.
\par - Verify that the desktop setup program is calling the correct AppMgr INI file, using a full pathname.
\par - There are various third-party desktop setup programs that 
will not correctly update the actual file sizes when overwriting existing files.  Since AppMgr will verify the actual file size with the embedded file size of the CAB file, make sure that the installed CAB file sizes are correct.  To ensure this happens f
or future upgrade scenarios, you can delete the known, existing CAB files on a reinstallation scenario.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 
\par 
\par 4.  WCELoad
\par ------------------
\par 
\par 4.1.\tab What does WCELoad do?
\par 
\par WCELoad is the Windows CE device tool that unpacks a given Windows CE CAB file to install the application on the device.  The CAB extension is associated with WCELoad, so the end-user can double-click on a CAB file to start the device installation.  Also,
 AppMgr launches WCELoad when it downloads the CAB files from the desktop to the device.
\par 
\par 
\par 4.2.\tab How do I call WCELoad?
\par 
\par Both the application creator and the end-user will not need to invoke WCELoad directly.  The application creator will indirectly invoke W
CELoad when AppMgr is called with an AppMgr INI file.  The end-user will indirectly invoke WCELoad when they double-click on a CAB file (that they may have downloaded from a website).
\par 
\par }}